<br>
We've had the retro discussion over and over again and one of the things I mentioned was that levels 1-10 are the wonder levels. When things are new and exciting. Then the grind sets in. Once I mentioned that almost everyone with few exceptions agreed that running from bats was fun.<br>
<br>
VI just robbed new players of that. Wheres the thrill of the CR in Befallen when you don't have to do it? Where's the fun in training the guards with a dozen bats because you wandered too far out of Felwithe?<br>
<br>
Add to that faster levelling in dungeons to encourage people to play there? Im sorry but that isn't the answer. The only way to get people into dungeons is not by rewarding them with extra XP for hunting there but penalise them with less exp in outdoor zones.<br>
<br>
Now there's an easier way to do this then nerfing the exp itself. Reduce the spawn rate of wandering mobs outside of known camps. This is where the idiots are playing. Lake of Ill Omen has goblin camps and the Sarnak Fortress which require as much skill as a dungeon. It's the idiots standing by the zones and pulling wanderers that are the people who don't learn mez and stuff.<br>
<br>
Same with DL. It's huge and can support a couple of harder camps, but the easiest way to get rid of the fools is by having monsters guards patrol KC’s walls. The idea is to look for all the safe spots and systematically eradicate them all.<br>
<br>
Another idea is to stop monsters from staying agroed for as long as they are on players who are running. With Velious they added code that made monsters give up the chase if the player got too far away yet with Kunark you can pull a mob, run halfway across the zone and have no fear that your mob will come to you eventually with no friends to help him. It's too easy and giving extra exp in dungeons will not detract what is effectively water from the path of least resistance.<br>
<br>
As for the spellbook I disagree with that too. No it serves no purpose and doesn't teach you anything. Maybe we should have no stamina bar or mana bar, in fact lets get give everyone 4000hp because having only 100hp at lower levels and having to sit down has no purpose. Oh no wait, high mana and hp are rewards for reaching higher levels and so was not looking at the book.<br>
<br>
When younger characters meditate they need to block out everything to regain the mana. This is consistent with meditation in real life. However I agree that looking at the book doesn't fit with that idea. Maybe the screen should just go black, or perhaps black and white and very blurred.<br>
